WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.040 --> 00:00:02.040
ETHAN KAY: If we were to
think about the biggest

00:00:02.040 --> 00:00:05.740
problems affecting our world,
any socially conscious person

00:00:05.740 --> 00:00:10.880
would have to include poverty,
disease, and climate change.

00:00:10.880 --> 00:00:14.070
And yet, there is one
thing that causes all three

00:00:14.070 --> 00:00:16.640
of these simultaneously,
that we pay

00:00:16.640 --> 00:00:20.120
almost no attention to, even
though a very good solution

00:00:20.120 --> 00:00:21.820
exists.

00:00:21.820 --> 00:00:24.210
It's one of the most
unreported stories about life

00:00:24.210 --> 00:00:25.810
in the developing world.

00:00:25.810 --> 00:00:29.010
And I'm here to
tell you about it.

00:00:29.010 --> 00:00:32.759
In 2005, I was working with
a rural community development

00:00:32.759 --> 00:00:35.570
NGO in Osmanabad, India.

00:00:35.570 --> 00:00:39.780
As part of my work, I conducted
in-depth interviews with women

00:00:39.780 --> 00:00:41.560
in their villages.

00:00:41.560 --> 00:00:45.210
I interviewed Mina in a
village called Bamaniwadi.

00:00:45.210 --> 00:00:48.040
At the time, she was cooking
lunch for her husband

00:00:48.040 --> 00:00:50.800
and her two-year-old daughter,
who was crawling next to her

00:00:50.800 --> 00:00:52.930
as she cooked.

00:00:52.930 --> 00:00:55.080
Like most women in
the village, Mina

00:00:55.080 --> 00:00:58.070
was cooking on an
indoor open fire.

00:00:58.070 --> 00:01:02.060
Her one-room hut was
thick with smoke.

00:01:02.060 --> 00:01:04.760
By 30 minutes into the
two-hour interview,

00:01:04.760 --> 00:01:06.660
everyone's eyes were watering.

00:01:06.660 --> 00:01:08.070
We were coughing.

00:01:08.070 --> 00:01:10.500
And I could barely breathe.

00:01:10.500 --> 00:01:13.290
I was horrified when I realized
that Mina and her family

00:01:13.290 --> 00:01:16.340
have to deal with
this on a daily basis.

00:01:16.340 --> 00:01:19.500
Yet, this is how nearly
half the world lives.

00:01:19.500 --> 00:01:25.597
Three billion people cook their
meals on indoor open fires.

00:01:25.597 --> 00:01:27.930
When we think about the biggest
killers of people living

00:01:27.930 --> 00:01:29.940
in poverty in the
developing world,

00:01:29.940 --> 00:01:34.870
we think about AIDS,
tuberculosis, and malaria.

00:01:34.870 --> 00:01:37.310
We don't think
about the kitchen.

00:01:37.310 --> 00:01:40.300
Yet, every year, over
four million people

00:01:40.300 --> 00:01:43.050
die from household air
pollution from cooking

00:01:43.050 --> 00:01:46.510
on a smoky open fire.

00:01:46.510 --> 00:01:48.770
It's like wiping out
half the population

00:01:48.770 --> 00:01:52.030
of New York City every year.

00:01:52.030 --> 00:01:54.920
Household air pollution
kills more people

00:01:54.920 --> 00:01:59.324
than AIDS, tuberculosis,
and malaria combined.

00:02:01.990 --> 00:02:03.890
How does this happen?

00:02:03.890 --> 00:02:06.700
Day after day, for up
to six hours a day,

00:02:06.700 --> 00:02:10.280
women like Mina cook their
meals on an indoor open fire.

00:02:10.280 --> 00:02:13.650
And when they do, they
breathe in the toxic smoke

00:02:13.650 --> 00:02:18.650
from the flames, which leads
to fatal respiratory diseases.

00:02:18.650 --> 00:02:21.220
Half a million of these
four million deaths

00:02:21.220 --> 00:02:23.890
are children under
the age of five.

00:02:23.890 --> 00:02:25.830
The biggest killer
of young children

00:02:25.830 --> 00:02:29.570
globally is smoke
from the open fire.

00:02:29.570 --> 00:02:31.950
So there's the serious problem.

00:02:31.950 --> 00:02:33.580
And yet, we're
completely ignoring it.

00:02:36.450 --> 00:02:39.520
In addition, these open
fires have an enormous impact

00:02:39.520 --> 00:02:40.980
on our environment.

00:02:40.980 --> 00:02:42.640
The smoke from
these fires contains

00:02:42.640 --> 00:02:44.900
something called
black carbon, which

00:02:44.900 --> 00:02:48.400
is the second biggest
contributor to climate change.

00:02:48.400 --> 00:02:51.550
According to the latest
statistics on black carbon,

00:02:51.550 --> 00:02:55.900
cooking on a smoky open fire
creates more black carbon

00:02:55.900 --> 00:02:58.771
than all of the world's
cars and trucks combined.

00:03:01.360 --> 00:03:03.210
So here's the situation.

00:03:03.210 --> 00:03:05.200
We have three billion
people cooking

00:03:05.200 --> 00:03:08.780
on smoky open fires with
devastating health and climate

00:03:08.780 --> 00:03:10.530
consequences.

00:03:10.530 --> 00:03:14.030
Solving this problem would
have an enormous impact

00:03:14.030 --> 00:03:17.570
on global health
and climate change.

00:03:17.570 --> 00:03:21.520
And there is a solution, the
production and distribution

00:03:21.520 --> 00:03:23.800
of ultra-clean cook stoves.

00:03:23.800 --> 00:03:26.960
These cook stoves dramatically
reduce smoke emissions

00:03:26.960 --> 00:03:29.350
and cut fuel consumption.

00:03:29.350 --> 00:03:31.780
And I'm going to turn it
over to my colleague, Ryan,

00:03:31.780 --> 00:03:34.894
to tell you more about
how this cook stove works.

00:03:34.894 --> 00:03:36.060
RYAN GIST: Thank you, Ethan.

00:03:36.060 --> 00:03:38.520
And thanks to Google
for hosting us today.

00:03:38.520 --> 00:03:40.300
So how does this product work?

00:03:40.300 --> 00:03:41.650
We've got one here.

00:03:41.650 --> 00:03:44.060
And the process starts
with the user feeding fuel

00:03:44.060 --> 00:03:46.090
into the side of the
stove and lighting it,

00:03:46.090 --> 00:03:48.760
just the same way they would
their traditional open fire.

00:03:48.760 --> 00:03:51.930
They use the same fuels,
whether it be wood or crop

00:03:51.930 --> 00:03:54.410
residue or even animal dung.

00:03:54.410 --> 00:03:56.280
But the difference
compared to the open fire

00:03:56.280 --> 00:03:58.960
is that when they light the
fire and heat is released,

00:03:58.960 --> 00:04:01.040
a small portion of
that heat energy

00:04:01.040 --> 00:04:03.300
is converted into
electrical energy.

00:04:03.300 --> 00:04:06.490
And that electricity is
used to turn a small fan,

00:04:06.490 --> 00:04:09.200
force feeding air into
the fire, bringing oxygen,

00:04:09.200 --> 00:04:11.860
and making for very
efficient clean combustion.

00:04:11.860 --> 00:04:15.000
The smoke is almost
eliminated, over 90% reduced.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:17.440
And the fire burns much
more efficiently, twice

00:04:17.440 --> 00:04:18.279
as efficiently.

00:04:18.279 --> 00:04:21.160
So that for any one
given cooking task,

00:04:21.160 --> 00:04:23.950
the user only needs to
feed half as much fuel.

00:04:23.950 --> 00:04:25.830
But it gets even
better than that

00:04:25.830 --> 00:04:28.590
because as the fire builds and
more heat energy is released,

00:04:28.590 --> 00:04:30.850
more electricity is
generated, to the point

00:04:30.850 --> 00:04:34.440
where it's more electricity
than is required for the fan.

00:04:34.440 --> 00:04:36.070
And that surplus
electricity can be

00:04:36.070 --> 00:04:38.802
passed to a USB port on
the side of the stove.

00:04:38.802 --> 00:04:40.260
You can see in this
instance, we're

00:04:40.260 --> 00:04:42.115
using a small LED
light, which can

00:04:42.115 --> 00:04:43.990
be used to light the
cooking area or the home

00:04:43.990 --> 00:04:45.380
for the evening.

00:04:45.380 --> 00:04:47.900
But even more importantly, in
areas of sub-Saharan Africa

00:04:47.900 --> 00:04:50.720
and India where mobile
phone adoption has outpaced

00:04:50.720 --> 00:04:54.070
the electricity grid, it still
generates enough electricity

00:04:54.070 --> 00:04:56.320
to be able to
charge a cell phone.

00:04:56.320 --> 00:04:59.780
So it's a really dramatic change
from other ways of solving

00:04:59.780 --> 00:05:01.270
this clean cooking issue.

00:05:01.270 --> 00:05:05.160
And it provides Ethan and his
team a totally different value

00:05:05.160 --> 00:05:07.100
proposition.

00:05:07.100 --> 00:05:10.960
This technology is enabled by
an electronic device called

00:05:10.960 --> 00:05:12.804
the thermoelectric generator.

00:05:12.804 --> 00:05:14.220
And there's a lot
of ways to think

00:05:14.220 --> 00:05:15.594
about a thermoelectric
generator.

00:05:15.594 --> 00:05:18.750
But today, let's consider it
like a solar panel for heat.

00:05:18.750 --> 00:05:21.100
So rather than converting
light into electricity,

00:05:21.100 --> 00:05:23.210
we're converting heat
into electricity.

00:05:23.210 --> 00:05:26.590
And this occurs due to a pair
of metals inside the device that

00:05:26.590 --> 00:05:28.044
have a very unique property.

00:05:28.044 --> 00:05:29.960
When one of them is hot
and the other is cold,

00:05:29.960 --> 00:05:32.490
they pass electrons
to one another.

00:05:32.490 --> 00:05:36.570
So the fire provides a very
convenient source of heat.

00:05:36.570 --> 00:05:39.947
And the cooler ambient air can
be used to cool the cold side.

00:05:39.947 --> 00:05:41.780
And that's the real
elegance in this design.

00:05:41.780 --> 00:05:43.570
It's the dual use
of this fan flow.

00:05:43.570 --> 00:05:46.200
That same air that we
talked about bringing oxygen

00:05:46.200 --> 00:05:48.710
to the fire to make it burn
cleanly and efficiently

00:05:48.710 --> 00:05:51.190
is the air that's used
to cool the cold side.

00:05:51.190 --> 00:05:53.400
And it gets preheated
in this process.

00:05:53.400 --> 00:05:54.910
So the fire gets what it needs.

00:05:54.910 --> 00:05:57.960
And the user is provided
with on demand electricity.

00:05:57.960 --> 00:06:00.950
So again, this just radically
changes the value proposition

00:06:00.950 --> 00:06:03.700
that Ethan can offer
to our customers.

00:06:03.700 --> 00:06:06.480
ETHAN KAY: At a
retail price of $50,

00:06:06.480 --> 00:06:09.830
the stove pays for itself in
seven months, based on fuel

00:06:09.830 --> 00:06:11.620
and electricity savings.

00:06:11.620 --> 00:06:13.190
And it gets even better.

00:06:13.190 --> 00:06:16.050
Since the stove reduces
carbon emissions,

00:06:16.050 --> 00:06:19.150
we can take advantage of
existing carbon credit offset

00:06:19.150 --> 00:06:22.210
programs to make this stove
affordable to the poorest

00:06:22.210 --> 00:06:24.240
of the poor.

00:06:24.240 --> 00:06:26.760
You may wonder why I'm
telling you all this.

00:06:26.760 --> 00:06:28.510
I'm not an engineer.

00:06:28.510 --> 00:06:30.400
I didn't design this stove.

00:06:30.400 --> 00:06:33.310
I'm just a guy from Cleveland,
Ohio, who has trouble making

00:06:33.310 --> 00:06:35.640
a grilled cheese sandwich.

00:06:35.640 --> 00:06:37.390
But after my
experience in hundreds

00:06:37.390 --> 00:06:39.940
of smoky homes
across rural India,

00:06:39.940 --> 00:06:43.230
I set myself the goal of
trying to solve this problem.

00:06:43.230 --> 00:06:44.680
So I tried to help
the NGO that I

00:06:44.680 --> 00:06:48.030
was working with to
distribute cook stoves to Mina

00:06:48.030 --> 00:06:50.480
and her neighbors.

00:06:50.480 --> 00:06:54.000
We marketed a stove by a
large British oil company.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:56.010
But it had some problems.

00:06:56.010 --> 00:06:58.880
It required expensive
fuel pellets, which people

00:06:58.880 --> 00:07:00.660
didn't want to pay for.

00:07:00.660 --> 00:07:04.900
And it needed electricity,
which many villages didn't have.

00:07:04.900 --> 00:07:06.550
So it sucked.

00:07:06.550 --> 00:07:10.540
And understanding why it sucked
was my PhD thesis in Management

00:07:10.540 --> 00:07:13.160
Studies from Oxford.

00:07:13.160 --> 00:07:15.880
What this large British oil
company didn't understand

00:07:15.880 --> 00:07:17.890
was how people in
rural India interact

00:07:17.890 --> 00:07:19.860
with their cooking environment.

00:07:19.860 --> 00:07:22.480
They didn't think about the
significance of the cook stove

00:07:22.480 --> 00:07:24.272
on daily life.

00:07:24.272 --> 00:07:25.730
What I saw in the
months and months

00:07:25.730 --> 00:07:29.920
that I spent in rural India was
that for technology to work,

00:07:29.920 --> 00:07:32.770
it has to be
culturally appropriate.

00:07:32.770 --> 00:07:35.880
And it's not just this big
oil company that got it wrong.

00:07:35.880 --> 00:07:39.250
So many previous attempts at
improving the lives of people

00:07:39.250 --> 00:07:41.300
living in poverty have failed.

00:07:41.300 --> 00:07:43.430
And I came to realize that
many of those failures

00:07:43.430 --> 00:07:46.060
did not employ a
user-centered approach.

00:07:46.060 --> 00:07:49.130
They failed to take into
account how real people live,

00:07:49.130 --> 00:07:53.910
their real behaviors
and cultural practices.

00:07:53.910 --> 00:07:55.770
So how to crack the
problem of cook stoves?

00:07:58.457 --> 00:08:00.040
When I really thought
about the people

00:08:00.040 --> 00:08:02.270
that I spent time
with in rural India,

00:08:02.270 --> 00:08:05.250
I realized that the stove
was not just an appliance,

00:08:05.250 --> 00:08:08.070
but the spiritual
center of their home.

00:08:08.070 --> 00:08:10.030
They saw this fire
in their kitchen

00:08:10.030 --> 00:08:14.560
as a domestic god, a
deity, and the flame

00:08:14.560 --> 00:08:17.940
as a spiritual messenger
between them and heaven.

00:08:17.940 --> 00:08:20.400
They prayed before
the stove daily

00:08:20.400 --> 00:08:23.080
and created rangoli,
artwork they

00:08:23.080 --> 00:08:25.880
drew around the stove
with colorful chalk

00:08:25.880 --> 00:08:28.745
to consecrate it, to
make it a sacred object.

00:08:31.840 --> 00:08:34.010
In much of the developing
world, the wife

00:08:34.010 --> 00:08:36.090
is responsible for the cooking.

00:08:36.090 --> 00:08:37.960
And she and the children
disproportionately

00:08:37.960 --> 00:08:39.690
suffer the health effects.

00:08:39.690 --> 00:08:42.460
But the husband
controls the money.

00:08:42.460 --> 00:08:45.760
So how could we get both
the wife and the husband

00:08:45.760 --> 00:08:49.270
to want to purchase
a clean cook stove?

00:08:49.270 --> 00:08:52.030
Most men in rural India
have a mobile phone,

00:08:52.030 --> 00:08:56.460
which they hope will help
them improve their livelihood.

00:08:56.460 --> 00:08:58.530
But many of them can't
charge the phone at home

00:08:58.530 --> 00:09:01.040
because they don't
have electricity.

00:09:01.040 --> 00:09:03.054
Usually, there's
a commercial kiosk

00:09:03.054 --> 00:09:04.470
a few miles away
where people have

00:09:04.470 --> 00:09:06.540
to pay to charge their phone.

00:09:06.540 --> 00:09:10.750
In Kenya, people pay $3 to $4
a month to charge their phone.

00:09:10.750 --> 00:09:12.080
That's two days' salary.

00:09:12.080 --> 00:09:15.950
That 7% of their income
just to charge their phone.

00:09:15.950 --> 00:09:19.350
But since our stove generates
more than enough electricity

00:09:19.350 --> 00:09:24.310
to charge their phone, men
really like this stove.

00:09:24.310 --> 00:09:27.370
There are also some
design considerations.

00:09:27.370 --> 00:09:30.510
People in different regions
cook different dishes.

00:09:30.510 --> 00:09:33.120
In Guatemala, they
make tortillas.

00:09:33.120 --> 00:09:36.330
And so they need a really
big cooking surface.

00:09:36.330 --> 00:09:39.630
In Ghana, they stir
large pots of stew.

00:09:39.630 --> 00:09:43.270
And so they need a sturdy
stove that won't topple.

00:09:43.270 --> 00:09:46.100
In north India, they make roti.

00:09:46.100 --> 00:09:48.630
And so they need a
really hot flame.

00:09:48.630 --> 00:09:50.650
So our stove needs
to be customized

00:09:50.650 --> 00:09:54.110
to serve different cultures.

00:09:54.110 --> 00:09:56.670
So how do we get these
stoves to people?

00:09:56.670 --> 00:09:58.395
Why don't we just
get a billion dollars

00:09:58.395 --> 00:10:04.310
from Warren Buffett or Google
and throw millions of stoves

00:10:04.310 --> 00:10:06.220
at rural India?

00:10:06.220 --> 00:10:08.500
It's not a good idea.

00:10:08.500 --> 00:10:10.130
People don't want charity.

00:10:10.130 --> 00:10:13.040
The people in rural India,
just like you and me,

00:10:13.040 --> 00:10:14.630
want their cherished
objects to be

00:10:14.630 --> 00:10:18.430
the result of their effort and
their economic achievement.

00:10:18.430 --> 00:10:22.290
Also, if they got the stoves
for free and they broke down

00:10:22.290 --> 00:10:23.770
and they couldn't
fix them, they'd

00:10:23.770 --> 00:10:27.960
go right back to cooking
on their open fire.

00:10:27.960 --> 00:10:31.100
We started designing
our business in 2010

00:10:31.100 --> 00:10:35.260
and thought that surely by now
we'd have a scaled up business.

00:10:35.260 --> 00:10:37.600
But we didn't anticipate
all of the hurdles that

00:10:37.600 --> 00:10:42.270
come with operating in rural
India and sub-Saharan Africa.

00:10:42.270 --> 00:10:47.620
For instance, in Uganda, the
tax rate on imported cook stoves

00:10:47.620 --> 00:10:50.150
is 60%.

00:10:50.150 --> 00:10:55.690
That means a $30 cook stove
costs the end customer $48.

00:10:55.690 --> 00:11:01.530
So we've had to get creative
and scrappy and lucky.

00:11:01.530 --> 00:11:05.070
Last January, the
vice-president of Uganda

00:11:05.070 --> 00:11:07.780
unexpectedly visited one
of our stove demonstrations

00:11:07.780 --> 00:11:09.600
in Kampala.

00:11:09.600 --> 00:11:12.860
He wanted to buy a stove,
but wanted to bargain down

00:11:12.860 --> 00:11:15.070
the retail price.

00:11:15.070 --> 00:11:16.960
We bargained back.

00:11:16.960 --> 00:11:19.820
We told him if his
government reduces

00:11:19.820 --> 00:11:22.490
taxes on this
life-enhancing product,

00:11:22.490 --> 00:11:24.560
we can reduce the cost
of the stove for him

00:11:24.560 --> 00:11:27.420
as well as the rest
of the country.

00:11:27.420 --> 00:11:29.420
After a year of
negotiations, we've

00:11:29.420 --> 00:11:33.790
managed to cut our tax rate
in Uganda by nearly half.

00:11:33.790 --> 00:11:37.220
We've also had some
unexpected setbacks.

00:11:37.220 --> 00:11:40.820
Our Ghana manager tried to
be culturally appropriate

00:11:40.820 --> 00:11:46.840
and ate a bush cat grilled
in his honor on the stove.

00:11:46.840 --> 00:11:50.870
Jan spent the next
month in the hospital.

00:11:50.870 --> 00:11:54.660
We've also had some
unexpected surprises.

00:11:54.660 --> 00:12:01.570
Our most successful sales agent
in India is also a magician.

00:12:01.570 --> 00:12:06.110
When demonstrating the stove,
Himanshu flicks a lit match

00:12:06.110 --> 00:12:08.580
from five feet away into
the mouth of the stove.

00:12:08.580 --> 00:12:11.620
And it immediately
lights the flame.

00:12:11.620 --> 00:12:13.630
Ryan and his engineering
team have also

00:12:13.630 --> 00:12:16.029
had to get creative and scrappy.

00:12:16.029 --> 00:12:17.070
RYAN GIST: Yeah, we have.

00:12:17.070 --> 00:12:18.674
And creative design
is one thing.

00:12:18.674 --> 00:12:21.090
But we've had to get creative
with the whole supply chain,

00:12:21.090 --> 00:12:22.770
as well.

00:12:22.770 --> 00:12:26.070
When your customers are very low
income and tightly constrained

00:12:26.070 --> 00:12:30.260
by their purchasing power,
pricing is critical.

00:12:30.260 --> 00:12:32.680
And as Ethan described, with
some of the taxes and tariffs

00:12:32.680 --> 00:12:35.910
that are imposed on us in
the markets we operate,

00:12:35.910 --> 00:12:38.200
there's a really powerful
compounding effect

00:12:38.200 --> 00:12:41.112
on the initial cost of goods.

00:12:41.112 --> 00:12:42.820
When we first got
started in all of this,

00:12:42.820 --> 00:12:45.530
we took a very standard
approach to component sourcing

00:12:45.530 --> 00:12:47.009
for the stove.

00:12:47.009 --> 00:12:48.050
We understood our system.

00:12:48.050 --> 00:12:49.690
We knew what each
piece needed to do.

00:12:49.690 --> 00:12:51.810
And we worked with
vendors to find

00:12:51.810 --> 00:12:53.980
catalog parts that
could get each one

00:12:53.980 --> 00:12:56.220
of those individual jobs done.

00:12:56.220 --> 00:12:58.680
We weren't experts in
thermoelectric generators.

00:12:58.680 --> 00:13:01.780
We weren't fan
designers or experts

00:13:01.780 --> 00:13:06.080
in power electronics
or metallurgists.

00:13:06.080 --> 00:13:09.330
We took their word
for it, really.

00:13:09.330 --> 00:13:11.260
But over the course
of the project

00:13:11.260 --> 00:13:13.810
and learning more
about the task at hand,

00:13:13.810 --> 00:13:15.820
we realized to really
delight our customer

00:13:15.820 --> 00:13:18.330
and to provide the product at
a price that they can afford,

00:13:18.330 --> 00:13:20.052
we had to do all those things.

00:13:20.052 --> 00:13:22.260
And so we've asked all the
members of the engineering

00:13:22.260 --> 00:13:24.670
team and the development
team to build expertise

00:13:24.670 --> 00:13:27.840
in totally new areas for them.

00:13:27.840 --> 00:13:30.630
I can walk you
through one example.

00:13:30.630 --> 00:13:33.095
At the core of the
system is the fan.

00:13:33.095 --> 00:13:35.560
And in the first
generation of the stove,

00:13:35.560 --> 00:13:39.110
we talked to every fan
manufacturer we could.

00:13:39.110 --> 00:13:42.230
And we identified a fan
that was a computer cooling

00:13:42.230 --> 00:13:45.230
fan, that was about right
for our application.

00:13:45.230 --> 00:13:48.160
These fans are mass produced
with all the benefits

00:13:48.160 --> 00:13:49.990
of economy of scale baked in.

00:13:49.990 --> 00:13:53.190
They appear in computers by
the millions the world over.

00:13:53.190 --> 00:13:54.940
So at about $3 a pop,
we thought we were

00:13:54.940 --> 00:13:56.920
getting a pretty good deal.

00:13:56.920 --> 00:14:00.270
The problem is that even $3
is a really significant chunk

00:14:00.270 --> 00:14:01.880
of our overall
cost of production

00:14:01.880 --> 00:14:04.340
for this affordable stove.

00:14:04.340 --> 00:14:06.300
And on top of that,
the fan was never

00:14:06.300 --> 00:14:07.865
designed for our application.

00:14:07.865 --> 00:14:10.240
So we had to actually purchase
a slightly larger version,

00:14:10.240 --> 00:14:13.670
knowing that it would run
not at peak efficiency.

00:14:13.670 --> 00:14:15.410
That simply wasn't
going to work.

00:14:15.410 --> 00:14:17.450
So we dug in, and like
I said, became experts.

00:14:17.450 --> 00:14:20.200
We studied compact fan design.

00:14:20.200 --> 00:14:23.530
We brought in tools to
do aerodynamic analysis

00:14:23.530 --> 00:14:26.390
on the duct work
inside of our product.

00:14:26.390 --> 00:14:28.140
We learned how to
control the fans.

00:14:28.140 --> 00:14:30.940
We even learned how to
design the electric motors

00:14:30.940 --> 00:14:32.439
that power of these fans.

00:14:32.439 --> 00:14:34.980
And the end result was that we
were able to short cut the fan

00:14:34.980 --> 00:14:38.530
manufacture entirely, source
a motor that could do the job

00:14:38.530 --> 00:14:42.670
for about $0.50, custom design
our own fan blades that could

00:14:42.670 --> 00:14:45.410
be injection molded
for about $0.10,

00:14:45.410 --> 00:14:47.850
run the fan from our
own power electronics,

00:14:47.850 --> 00:14:51.150
and incorporate the rest of
the housing into the plastic

00:14:51.150 --> 00:14:53.380
enclosure already
part of the product.

00:14:53.380 --> 00:14:56.250
And so in the end, a
component that cost $3 we now

00:14:56.250 --> 00:14:59.880
can make for under $1, saving
over 70% on that component

00:14:59.880 --> 00:15:00.630
alone.

00:15:00.630 --> 00:15:03.230
And we fought similar sourcing
battles across the product

00:15:03.230 --> 00:15:06.280
all over, in the metals in
the stove, the electronics,

00:15:06.280 --> 00:15:09.030
the thermoelectric.

00:15:09.030 --> 00:15:12.640
But the point is that we really
had to dive and become experts.

00:15:12.640 --> 00:15:13.887
And pricing is one half.

00:15:13.887 --> 00:15:15.720
But we also need to
understand the customer.

00:15:15.720 --> 00:15:17.407
And we pushed
really hard to have

00:15:17.407 --> 00:15:18.990
every engineer on
the development team

00:15:18.990 --> 00:15:22.790
pay equal attention to our
users and the user needs.

00:15:22.790 --> 00:15:26.830
We spent weeks and months in
the field with Ethan's team,

00:15:26.830 --> 00:15:30.282
observing cooking, watching
household energy management,

00:15:30.282 --> 00:15:32.240
and sitting down with
the cooks to really learn

00:15:32.240 --> 00:15:34.190
how they interact
with the stove, what

00:15:34.190 --> 00:15:37.406
the potential pitfalls
and pain points might be.

00:15:37.406 --> 00:15:38.780
We learned a lot
in this process.

00:15:38.780 --> 00:15:40.830
I always say a week
in the field can

00:15:40.830 --> 00:15:43.860
be more informative
than a month in the lab.

00:15:43.860 --> 00:15:46.430
And even as recently
as late last year,

00:15:46.430 --> 00:15:49.810
we've made some pretty
key understandings

00:15:49.810 --> 00:15:51.670
during this process.

00:15:51.670 --> 00:15:54.760
One specific incident
late last year,

00:15:54.760 --> 00:15:56.080
we were watching people cook.

00:15:56.080 --> 00:15:58.170
And in some regions,
for certain dishes,

00:15:58.170 --> 00:16:00.750
rather than just an hour or
two hours worth of cooking,

00:16:00.750 --> 00:16:02.950
they cook nearly all day,
for three, four, five

00:16:02.950 --> 00:16:04.237
hours at a time.

00:16:04.237 --> 00:16:06.070
And during these really
long duration burns,

00:16:06.070 --> 00:16:08.750
some of the fuel doesn't
quite fully combust.

00:16:08.750 --> 00:16:10.650
And you build
charcoal in the stove.

00:16:10.650 --> 00:16:12.460
This charcoal builds
up and eventually,

00:16:12.460 --> 00:16:13.990
over the course of
four hours or so,

00:16:13.990 --> 00:16:15.350
can fill up the whole chamber.

00:16:15.350 --> 00:16:17.350
And so you need to remove
that charcoal in order

00:16:17.350 --> 00:16:20.064
to keep cooking,
to feed fresh fuel.

00:16:20.064 --> 00:16:21.480
Well, the problem
is we've now got

00:16:21.480 --> 00:16:23.970
a cook who's pulling out
a large burning stick

00:16:23.970 --> 00:16:26.510
and essentially holding an
open fire now in their hand,

00:16:26.510 --> 00:16:28.450
emitting all the smoke
that an open fire does.

00:16:28.450 --> 00:16:31.980
And what we saw was that during
this process of pulling out

00:16:31.980 --> 00:16:33.770
the burning fuel,
clearing the charcoal,

00:16:33.770 --> 00:16:35.699
and putting it back
in, all that smoke

00:16:35.699 --> 00:16:37.490
we had just saved over
the last three hours

00:16:37.490 --> 00:16:39.480
was now emitted into the home.

00:16:39.480 --> 00:16:41.820
So we knew it was an issue
that had to be solved.

00:16:41.820 --> 00:16:43.060
We came back into the lab.

00:16:43.060 --> 00:16:46.340
We built out capability to
do long duration burns here

00:16:46.340 --> 00:16:47.820
in our labs for hours on end.

00:16:47.820 --> 00:16:50.170
We sourced the
appropriate fuel to be

00:16:50.170 --> 00:16:51.940
able to simulate conditions.

00:16:51.940 --> 00:16:54.150
And we re-tuned the
entire injection scheme

00:16:54.150 --> 00:16:56.240
to make sure that not
only the flame was burning

00:16:56.240 --> 00:16:58.650
clean and efficiently, but
this charcoal was fully

00:16:58.650 --> 00:16:59.850
combusted and used.

00:16:59.850 --> 00:17:03.616
We eliminated the need for this
charcoal clearing exercise.

00:17:03.616 --> 00:17:04.740
And so I think we're close.

00:17:04.740 --> 00:17:06.280
We've got the right product.

00:17:06.280 --> 00:17:08.474
We're zeroing in
on the cost target.

00:17:08.474 --> 00:17:10.140
And it's really up
to Ethan and his team

00:17:10.140 --> 00:17:14.232
to go get these stoves into all
the households that need them.

00:17:14.232 --> 00:17:15.690
ETHAN KAY: Our
business is on track

00:17:15.690 --> 00:17:17.920
to be self-sustaining
and profitable.

00:17:17.920 --> 00:17:20.329
But it's going to take a
lot of patience and capital

00:17:20.329 --> 00:17:21.680
to get there.

00:17:21.680 --> 00:17:23.680
Fortunately, we've
built this patience

00:17:23.680 --> 00:17:25.560
into our business model.

00:17:25.560 --> 00:17:29.460
In addition to selling cook
stoves in the developing world,

00:17:29.460 --> 00:17:32.210
we also commercialized a line
of camping products, which

00:17:32.210 --> 00:17:35.860
we sell to outdoor recreation
customers in the US

00:17:35.860 --> 00:17:38.210
and over 70 other countries.

00:17:38.210 --> 00:17:42.300
We call this business
model parallel innovation.

00:17:42.300 --> 00:17:45.810
This is not a TOMS shoes,
one-for-one handout model.

00:17:45.810 --> 00:17:48.950
This is about reinvesting
near-term revenue

00:17:48.950 --> 00:17:51.100
from the sale of
our camping products

00:17:51.100 --> 00:17:53.620
to incubate the emerging
markets business until it's

00:17:53.620 --> 00:17:55.640
commercially self-sufficient.

00:17:55.640 --> 00:17:57.530
I'd love to talk to
any of you afterward

00:17:57.530 --> 00:17:59.661
about how we can make this
business model even more

00:17:59.661 --> 00:18:00.160
sustainable.

00:18:03.270 --> 00:18:09.030
Around 1440, Johannes
Gutenberg, an entrepreneur

00:18:09.030 --> 00:18:14.100
with a great beard, set out
to develop the printing press.

00:18:14.100 --> 00:18:17.710
At the time, scribes
wrote books by hand.

00:18:17.710 --> 00:18:21.240
Yet, the challenge of inventing
a printing press were daunting.

00:18:21.240 --> 00:18:24.440
Civilizations had been
trying for thousands of years

00:18:24.440 --> 00:18:27.000
to mechanically
reproduce texts--

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:31.320
the Minoans, the
Greeks, the Chinese.

00:18:31.320 --> 00:18:33.150
Yet, it never took off.

00:18:33.150 --> 00:18:35.440
In each case, there
was something missing

00:18:35.440 --> 00:18:38.290
that was crucial to
mass uptake, whether it

00:18:38.290 --> 00:18:42.020
was the invention of
paper or the alphabet

00:18:42.020 --> 00:18:47.030
or expanded literacy or
buy-in from religious elites.

00:18:47.030 --> 00:18:49.470
It wasn't just a
technology problem.

00:18:49.470 --> 00:18:51.650
For printing to catch
on, all of these

00:18:51.650 --> 00:18:54.520
technical and cultural
and social elements

00:18:54.520 --> 00:18:56.870
needed to align.

00:18:56.870 --> 00:18:59.480
Gutenberg understood the need
to develop a contextually

00:18:59.480 --> 00:19:01.280
appropriate solution.

00:19:01.280 --> 00:19:04.880
For instance, he
designed his typeface

00:19:04.880 --> 00:19:07.280
to look like
scribal handwriting,

00:19:07.280 --> 00:19:09.330
so that it was
consistent with the look

00:19:09.330 --> 00:19:12.880
of valuable illuminated
manuscripts.

00:19:12.880 --> 00:19:15.470
He didn't want to break
with existing culture,

00:19:15.470 --> 00:19:19.280
or else he'd alienate
prospective buyers.

00:19:19.280 --> 00:19:22.780
Also, since the church
controlled the book industry,

00:19:22.780 --> 00:19:25.710
he, just like us
with cook stoves,

00:19:25.710 --> 00:19:28.640
needed to get religious
leaders on board.

00:19:28.640 --> 00:19:32.430
He made his first product
the Bible, which as we know,

00:19:32.430 --> 00:19:34.890
went viral.

00:19:34.890 --> 00:19:37.110
This was one of the most
important inventions

00:19:37.110 --> 00:19:40.950
in world history because it led
to the explosion of knowledge.

00:19:40.950 --> 00:19:44.290
But it only took off because it
was consistent with the social,

00:19:44.290 --> 00:19:48.060
cultural, and religious context.

00:19:48.060 --> 00:19:51.410
Today, as in Gutenberg's
time, in order

00:19:51.410 --> 00:19:54.290
to design solutions
for any community,

00:19:54.290 --> 00:19:56.460
particularly in the
developing world,

00:19:56.460 --> 00:19:58.790
it's important to acquire
an in-depth understanding

00:19:58.790 --> 00:20:01.510
of local users and
their motivations.

00:20:01.510 --> 00:20:04.400
It's important to understand
how real people live,

00:20:04.400 --> 00:20:07.280
their culture,
and their beliefs.

00:20:07.280 --> 00:20:09.990
If we do this
intelligently, we can

00:20:09.990 --> 00:20:13.470
solve some of the world's
most serious problems.

00:20:13.470 --> 00:20:17.290
This is the BioLite home stove.

00:20:17.290 --> 00:20:20.130
Ryan and I are 34.

00:20:20.130 --> 00:20:22.700
By the time we're 40,
let's make sure there

00:20:22.700 --> 00:20:25.290
are millions and millions
of these stoves saving lives

00:20:25.290 --> 00:20:27.630
across India and Africa.

00:20:27.630 --> 00:20:28.520
Thank you.

