00:20:39.420 --> 00:20:42.440
AUDIENCE: Hi, my name is Chris.

00:20:42.440 --> 00:20:46.670
Health data is notoriously
difficult to gather.

00:20:46.670 --> 00:20:49.450
So could you talk a little bit
about the methodology for how

00:20:49.450 --> 00:20:51.390
you quantified this
problem, like how

00:20:51.390 --> 00:20:54.840
you're attributing these
premature deaths to the smoke?

00:20:54.840 --> 00:20:56.410
Is it condition-based?

00:20:56.410 --> 00:20:59.386
I would love to hear
more about that.

00:20:59.386 --> 00:21:00.510
ETHAN KAY: Do you want me--

00:21:00.510 --> 00:21:01.260
RYAN GIST: Yeah, you
should take that.

00:21:01.260 --> 00:21:03.347
I mean, we don't develop
that data ourselves.

00:21:03.347 --> 00:21:04.430
But you could speak to it.

00:21:04.430 --> 00:21:07.520
ETHAN KAY: So the data on the
magnitude of deaths attributed

00:21:07.520 --> 00:21:10.130
to household air pollution are
provided by the World Health

00:21:10.130 --> 00:21:12.600
Organization.

00:21:12.600 --> 00:21:16.810
And the primary deaths are
both respiratory disease

00:21:16.810 --> 00:21:22.410
and cardiovascular disease
and cardiopulmonary disease.

00:21:22.410 --> 00:21:27.980
There's been a big challenge
in the global public health

00:21:27.980 --> 00:21:32.280
community, not around
attributing deaths

00:21:32.280 --> 00:21:36.260
from these diseases, but
rather in quantifying

00:21:36.260 --> 00:21:41.240
the health impact of stoves like
these to address those deaths.

00:21:41.240 --> 00:21:45.530
So the public health
community argues

00:21:45.530 --> 00:21:50.590
that you need a 90% reduction
in particulate matter

00:21:50.590 --> 00:21:54.520
in order to mitigate the
risk of respiratory disease.

00:21:54.520 --> 00:21:57.860
And if we can nerd
it out for a second,

00:21:57.860 --> 00:22:03.320
the relationship between
respiratory disease and air

00:22:03.320 --> 00:22:05.470
pollution is not linear.

00:22:05.470 --> 00:22:06.860
It's logarithmic.

00:22:06.860 --> 00:22:12.540
So you need literally a 10x
reduction from an open fire

00:22:12.540 --> 00:22:15.410
in order to have a 50%
reduction in the risk

00:22:15.410 --> 00:22:17.340
factor for respiratory disease.

00:22:17.340 --> 00:22:20.550
And so the first thing that
we as an organization did

00:22:20.550 --> 00:22:24.470
was, have had to validate
in our own lab, which

00:22:24.470 --> 00:22:27.490
is built to the same standards,
and Ryan can elaborate on this,

00:22:27.490 --> 00:22:32.200
as the US EPA that our stove
produces smoke in laboratory

00:22:32.200 --> 00:22:35.850
conditions by at least
90%, which we've done so,

00:22:35.850 --> 00:22:40.140
and have also had the EPA
and the government of India

00:22:40.140 --> 00:22:43.120
and other independent bodies
independently verify that.

00:22:43.120 --> 00:22:48.960
We then took stoves to the
field and have done studies

00:22:48.960 --> 00:22:52.790
with independent testing groups
like Berkeley Air Monitoring,

00:22:52.790 --> 00:22:54.850
which is a group
out of California,

00:22:54.850 --> 00:22:58.376
to validate that with the types
of fuels that people are using

00:22:58.376 --> 00:23:01.000
and the way that they're used to
feeding the fuels that it also

00:23:01.000 --> 00:23:05.400
achieves a 90% reduction
in respiratory disease.

00:23:05.400 --> 00:23:07.420
And we've done that, as well.

00:23:07.420 --> 00:23:15.340
And then the final step
is the gold standard

00:23:15.340 --> 00:23:18.650
in research methods, which is
a randomized control trial.

00:23:18.650 --> 00:23:20.950
And so for the last
2 and 1/2 years,

00:23:20.950 --> 00:23:24.250
BioLite has been participating
in the world's largest

00:23:24.250 --> 00:23:28.370
randomized controlled trial of
the health impact of this cook

00:23:28.370 --> 00:23:31.550
stove on young children.

00:23:31.550 --> 00:23:34.560
And it's a National
Institute of Health funded

00:23:34.560 --> 00:23:38.630
study, administered by Columbia
University's School of Public

00:23:38.630 --> 00:23:40.870
Health and the Ghanaian
Ministry of Health.

00:23:40.870 --> 00:23:45.340
And the results aren't out yet,
but that's the third piece,

00:23:45.340 --> 00:23:49.687
validating that these stoves
have impact on villagers.

00:23:49.687 --> 00:23:50.437
RYAN GIST: Thanks.

00:23:53.156 --> 00:23:54.530
AUDIENCE: Hey,
how does the stove

00:23:54.530 --> 00:23:56.750
compare with the typical
rocket stove design?

00:23:56.750 --> 00:23:59.862
Is it basically the same thing
or a completely different idea?

00:23:59.862 --> 00:24:01.820
RYAN GIST: Well, totally
different in that it's

00:24:01.820 --> 00:24:03.360
a forced draft stove.

00:24:03.360 --> 00:24:05.457
So it does have a rocket
stove architecture.

00:24:05.457 --> 00:24:07.040
And for everybody
else out here that's

00:24:07.040 --> 00:24:08.860
not familiar with
the rocket stove,

00:24:08.860 --> 00:24:11.772
it's a basic stove
architecture that's essentially

00:24:11.772 --> 00:24:12.980
like a chimney in your house.

00:24:12.980 --> 00:24:15.190
You've got this L
shape that's properly

00:24:15.190 --> 00:24:17.950
sized in terms of
the inlet and also

00:24:17.950 --> 00:24:19.990
the outlet of the
top of the stove.

00:24:19.990 --> 00:24:22.910
And so as the fire
releases heat,

00:24:22.910 --> 00:24:25.650
it induces this natural
draft, pulls air

00:24:25.650 --> 00:24:27.885
in from the ambient
through the fire,

00:24:27.885 --> 00:24:29.010
and then comes out the top.

00:24:29.010 --> 00:24:31.343
And the other thing that's
important in the rocket stove

00:24:31.343 --> 00:24:33.040
architecture is
all the insulation

00:24:33.040 --> 00:24:34.400
that's built around that.

00:24:34.400 --> 00:24:36.510
And so there's a
bunch of insulation

00:24:36.510 --> 00:24:40.540
between this outer wall and
the hot wall inside the chamber

00:24:40.540 --> 00:24:42.770
so that all the heat really
gets directed directly

00:24:42.770 --> 00:24:47.250
to the cooking surface rather
than lost out to the ambient.

00:24:47.250 --> 00:24:50.110
So a rocket stove can
improve the fuel efficiency.

00:24:50.110 --> 00:24:52.569
But the problem is, for each
gram of fuel that you burn,

00:24:52.569 --> 00:24:54.110
you're still emitting
all this smoke.

00:24:54.110 --> 00:24:56.300
You're not really getting
complete combustion.

00:24:56.300 --> 00:24:58.730
You're not getting intimate
mixing between the oxygen

00:24:58.730 --> 00:24:59.970
and the fuel molecules.

00:24:59.970 --> 00:25:01.770
And the fan, with
our injection array,

00:25:01.770 --> 00:25:04.660
getting turbulent mixing
at each jet location really

00:25:04.660 --> 00:25:06.330
is what changes that.

00:25:06.330 --> 00:25:08.660
So we've used the
rocket architecture

00:25:08.660 --> 00:25:10.300
to improve the fuel economy.

00:25:10.300 --> 00:25:12.300
And then we've used our
air injection technology

00:25:12.300 --> 00:25:15.310
to make sure each
gram of fuel released

00:25:15.310 --> 00:25:18.174
is 90% less particulate matter.

00:25:18.174 --> 00:25:20.340
AUDIENCE: And did you
consider any exhaust solutions

00:25:20.340 --> 00:25:24.920
because burning the fuel
more cleanly is one good way.

00:25:24.920 --> 00:25:27.390
But another obvious thing
that pops into my mind

00:25:27.390 --> 00:25:29.340
is, if the smoke gets
exhausted outside

00:25:29.340 --> 00:25:31.840
rather than just being released
in the air inside the house.

00:25:31.840 --> 00:25:32.120
RYAN GIST: Sure.

00:25:32.120 --> 00:25:34.450
AUDIENCE: Would there be a
plug-in or some kind of a way?

00:25:34.450 --> 00:25:35.850
Or is that just not
practical with the way

00:25:35.850 --> 00:25:37.090
that these stoves
are typically used?

00:25:37.090 --> 00:25:39.173
RYAN GIST: It can be
practical in certain markets.

00:25:39.173 --> 00:25:41.270
Ethan showed you
the cooking style

00:25:41.270 --> 00:25:43.900
in Latin America, which is
on a wide plancha stove.

00:25:43.900 --> 00:25:47.082
And those are usually inbuilt
stoves that are fixed in place.

00:25:47.082 --> 00:25:48.790
And adding a chimney
to a stove like that

00:25:48.790 --> 00:25:51.507
can really dramatically
improve indoor air pollution.

00:25:51.507 --> 00:25:53.090
There are a couple
problems with that.

00:25:53.090 --> 00:25:54.506
I mean, for one,
you're not really

00:25:54.506 --> 00:25:56.360
addressing the
environmental impacts

00:25:56.360 --> 00:25:57.830
of all that black carbon.

00:25:57.830 --> 00:26:00.300
The black carbon is
a huge forcing factor

00:26:00.300 --> 00:26:01.580
on global warming potential.

00:26:01.580 --> 00:26:03.540
So we'd rather burn
it to completion

00:26:03.540 --> 00:26:05.340
than just dump it outside.

00:26:05.340 --> 00:26:08.890
But also, there are cultural
contexts in daily use modes

00:26:08.890 --> 00:26:11.130
where the stove really
needs to be flexible.

00:26:11.130 --> 00:26:13.550
And people need to be able
to put different cooking

00:26:13.550 --> 00:26:14.620
implements on top of it.

00:26:14.620 --> 00:26:18.580
So a compact, portable stove
like this is much more useful.

00:26:18.580 --> 00:26:20.547
It requires a lot
less behavior change

00:26:20.547 --> 00:26:22.380
than something that's
inbuilt with a chimney

00:26:22.380 --> 00:26:24.764
that pipes the flow
outside of the home.

00:26:24.764 --> 00:26:27.295
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:26:27.295 --> 00:26:29.295
AUDIENCE: Do you do all
your manufacturing here?

00:26:29.295 --> 00:26:32.000
Or do you try to have a local
supply chain in the countries

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:33.444
where you're selling the stoves?

00:26:36.206 --> 00:26:38.080
RYAN GIST: We can tag
team this one, I guess.

00:26:38.080 --> 00:26:40.880
I mean, currently the stoves
are produced in China.

00:26:40.880 --> 00:26:44.320
That's the cheapest way we
can generate them and have

00:26:44.320 --> 00:26:47.720
the quality control that we need
for the electronics components.

00:26:47.720 --> 00:26:51.370
We're working in both
India and East Africa

00:26:51.370 --> 00:26:53.780
to find options
for local assembly

00:26:53.780 --> 00:26:57.659
and some local production of
the metallic parts of the stove.

00:26:57.659 --> 00:26:59.950
You can imagine that the cast
iron pieces and the metal

00:26:59.950 --> 00:27:01.229
pieces are heavy.

00:27:01.229 --> 00:27:03.020
They're expensive to
ship around the world.

00:27:03.020 --> 00:27:07.250
So bringing those pieces of
the production in-country

00:27:07.250 --> 00:27:09.070
can reduce our tariff rates.

00:27:09.070 --> 00:27:12.680
It can invigorate local
businesses in those countries

00:27:12.680 --> 00:27:15.217
and also reduce the
shipping costs for us.

00:27:15.217 --> 00:27:16.800
But in order to keep
the quality where

00:27:16.800 --> 00:27:18.300
it needs to be on
our electronics

00:27:18.300 --> 00:27:21.180
components and the fan and
some of the internal geometry,

00:27:21.180 --> 00:27:23.479
we'll probably keep most
of that in southern China

00:27:23.479 --> 00:27:24.270
for the time being.

00:27:26.895 --> 00:27:27.770
AUDIENCE: Hey, there.

00:27:27.770 --> 00:27:30.020
Thanks for coming.

00:27:30.020 --> 00:27:31.610
I'm curious about
a couple of things.

00:27:31.610 --> 00:27:33.310
One is around your supply chain.

00:27:33.310 --> 00:27:35.690
I'd like to hear some of
the challenges of getting

00:27:35.690 --> 00:27:38.710
this product to the
people that need it.

00:27:38.710 --> 00:27:40.740
And things break.

00:27:40.740 --> 00:27:43.360
Once they break, what kind
of challenges and what kind

00:27:43.360 --> 00:27:46.330
of solutions have you come up
with for helping the people

00:27:46.330 --> 00:27:49.270
there repair their own devices?

00:27:49.270 --> 00:27:50.760
ETHAN KAY: Sure.

00:27:50.760 --> 00:27:54.820
So the first time that
we shipped as pilot units

00:27:54.820 --> 00:28:01.890
to India, I think
40% of them ended up

00:28:01.890 --> 00:28:04.650
smashed by the time they
reached the end user.

00:28:04.650 --> 00:28:08.310
And it turned out that
they were being thrown off

00:28:08.310 --> 00:28:12.920
the top of trains and buses.

00:28:12.920 --> 00:28:18.025
And so we had to augment our
packaging to address that.

00:28:20.720 --> 00:28:23.280
One of the biggest challenges
in the business model

00:28:23.280 --> 00:28:26.130
is what we call last
mile distribution, which

00:28:26.130 --> 00:28:30.190
is, once you've
left a city and have

00:28:30.190 --> 00:28:33.270
to get the product
to a villager's home,

00:28:33.270 --> 00:28:39.540
the roads, if there are roads at
all, they're very poor quality.

00:28:39.540 --> 00:28:46.160
And so we've designed these--

00:28:46.160 --> 00:28:49.630
I don't know if any
of you have seen

00:28:49.630 --> 00:28:52.850
on the back of motorcycles,
there are these pizza boxes

00:28:52.850 --> 00:28:54.870
sometimes in the
developing world.

00:28:54.870 --> 00:28:58.640
Domino's delivers their
pizzas with these, like,

00:28:58.640 --> 00:29:00.680
boxes on the back of motorbikes.

00:29:00.680 --> 00:29:03.090
And so we've designed
a similar box

00:29:03.090 --> 00:29:09.580
for transporting our stoves on
motorbikes because our village

00:29:09.580 --> 00:29:11.410
distribution agents
ride motorbikes

00:29:11.410 --> 00:29:13.780
to get stoves to end user.

00:29:13.780 --> 00:29:15.700
And we've even
designed an apparatus

00:29:15.700 --> 00:29:17.820
that can allow you to
carry six of these stoves

00:29:17.820 --> 00:29:22.410
on the back of the bike
in a pretty safe way.

00:29:22.410 --> 00:29:28.920
Beyond that, we really think
that customer engagement

00:29:28.920 --> 00:29:31.220
starts at the point of sale.

00:29:31.220 --> 00:29:32.810
It doesn't stop then.

00:29:32.810 --> 00:29:37.620
And so we've invested really
heavily in after sale service.

00:29:37.620 --> 00:29:41.590
And so, I'll just share
a couple aspects of it.

00:29:41.590 --> 00:29:44.110
The first is that we've set
up a call center in each

00:29:44.110 --> 00:29:47.590
of our markets that follows up
with every one of our customers

00:29:47.590 --> 00:29:51.330
who's purchased the stove,
first a couple weeks

00:29:51.330 --> 00:29:53.830
after the point of sale to make
sure that they were properly

00:29:53.830 --> 00:29:55.970
trained when they
were sold the product

00:29:55.970 --> 00:29:59.300
and to make sure they don't
have immediate user issues, then

00:29:59.300 --> 00:30:03.390
at six months and a year
after to find out, do they

00:30:03.390 --> 00:30:06.060
like the stove, is it delivering
on its feature set, would they

00:30:06.060 --> 00:30:09.230
recommend it to
others, et cetera.

00:30:09.230 --> 00:30:13.010
And then in addition to
that, Ryan and his team

00:30:13.010 --> 00:30:18.190
have designed the stove to
be very, very easy to repair.

00:30:18.190 --> 00:30:19.690
And maybe you can
elaborate on that.

00:30:19.690 --> 00:30:21.689
RYAN GIST: Yeah, no, I'm
glad you brought it up.

00:30:21.689 --> 00:30:23.350
I was going to add
to that at the end.

00:30:23.350 --> 00:30:26.300
But essentially, there's two
main halves of the stove.

00:30:26.300 --> 00:30:28.930
There's the metallic
stove body that's

00:30:28.930 --> 00:30:32.180
the heat containing
functional part, and then

00:30:32.180 --> 00:30:35.210
the power electronics in
our power pack back here.

00:30:35.210 --> 00:30:38.420
And by making those two
somewhat modular and really

00:30:38.420 --> 00:30:41.260
simple to join to
one another, we

00:30:41.260 --> 00:30:43.580
can identify the
particular issue

00:30:43.580 --> 00:30:45.510
that a user might
have, and address that

00:30:45.510 --> 00:30:48.110
with just a component
replacement that our field

00:30:48.110 --> 00:30:51.060
agents are very capable of
implementing in the field.

00:30:51.060 --> 00:30:53.922
And so if the stove has
been in use for many years,

00:30:53.922 --> 00:30:55.630
maybe there is some
corrosion inside here

00:30:55.630 --> 00:30:57.270
and they need a new stove body.

00:30:57.270 --> 00:30:59.280
We can replace that with
the existing power pack

00:30:59.280 --> 00:31:01.320
they have at a reduced cost.

00:31:01.320 --> 00:31:05.880
If someone's thrown some liquid
inside the thing or someone's

00:31:05.880 --> 00:31:08.330
grabbed it and somehow
damaged the power pack,

00:31:08.330 --> 00:31:11.160
we can bring a
replacement power pack

00:31:11.160 --> 00:31:13.830
and split that supply
chain up a little bit.

00:31:13.830 --> 00:31:16.160
ETHAN KAY: And currently,
our average repair time

00:31:16.160 --> 00:31:19.560
across markets is three
days from the point

00:31:19.560 --> 00:31:22.000
that the customer experiences
an issue to the point

00:31:22.000 --> 00:31:23.306
that it's been solved for.

00:31:23.306 --> 00:31:27.280
So we've tried to decentralize
after sales service

00:31:27.280 --> 00:31:32.583
to allow for very
efficient repairs.

00:31:32.583 --> 00:31:33.291
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:31:33.291 --> 00:31:35.014
ETHAN KAY: Thanks.

00:31:35.014 --> 00:31:35.680
AUDIENCE: Hello.

00:31:35.680 --> 00:31:36.699
I have two questions.

00:31:36.699 --> 00:31:38.490
First, I want to know
if you had considered

00:31:38.490 --> 00:31:42.040
creating a bigger opening
for bigger pieces of wood.

00:31:42.040 --> 00:31:44.760
And the other question is,
could you please describe again

00:31:44.760 --> 00:31:47.224
how you reduced the smoke.

00:31:47.224 --> 00:31:47.890
RYAN GIST: Sure.

00:31:47.890 --> 00:31:48.620
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:31:48.620 --> 00:31:49.410
RYAN GIST: I'll
take both of those.

00:31:49.410 --> 00:31:51.250
You must be a
stove user yourself

00:31:51.250 --> 00:31:54.820
because that's the number one
feedback we get in the regions

00:31:54.820 --> 00:31:57.320
that we operate is like, we
need a bigger fuel mouth.

00:31:57.320 --> 00:32:01.490
Oftentimes, people are literally
tearing limbs off of trees

00:32:01.490 --> 00:32:03.925
and lighting the end of it
and continually feeding that

00:32:03.925 --> 00:32:04.550
into the stove.

00:32:04.550 --> 00:32:07.730
So that's definitely something
we're working to optimize.

00:32:07.730 --> 00:32:09.470
There is a new version
of this stove that

00:32:09.470 --> 00:32:10.360
will be coming out this year.

00:32:10.360 --> 00:32:12.180
The mouth has been
increased a little bit.

00:32:12.180 --> 00:32:15.080
But the trade there is
that as you open the mouth,

00:32:15.080 --> 00:32:17.760
you're now exposing all
that heat and radiation

00:32:17.760 --> 00:32:19.590
to the environment.

00:32:19.590 --> 00:32:22.514
And that's really one of the
key factors of the rocket stove

00:32:22.514 --> 00:32:24.430
architecture that we
talked about a minute ago

00:32:24.430 --> 00:32:26.410
is that by containing
all of that

00:32:26.410 --> 00:32:29.550
and not allowing the radiation
to get out into the world,

00:32:29.550 --> 00:32:31.740
you're improving the fuel
efficiency of the stove.

00:32:31.740 --> 00:32:33.300
So there's kind of
a balancing point.

00:32:33.300 --> 00:32:35.450
And we're trying to find out
exactly where that point is.

00:32:35.450 --> 00:32:38.010
We believe it's a little bit
larger than what you see here,

00:32:38.010 --> 00:32:42.480
but not so much larger that we
really lose fuel efficiency.

00:32:42.480 --> 00:32:44.690
And in terms of
eliminating the smoke,

00:32:44.690 --> 00:32:47.370
it's really just chemistry.

00:32:47.370 --> 00:32:49.430
I have a background in
aerospace engineering.

00:32:49.430 --> 00:32:51.430
I did combustion engineering
at my previous job.

00:32:51.430 --> 00:32:54.160
And it's really all about
getting intimate contact

00:32:54.160 --> 00:32:56.550
with fuel molecules
and oxygen molecules,

00:32:56.550 --> 00:32:58.770
and making sure they
can interact in a place

00:32:58.770 --> 00:33:00.170
where they're nice and hot.

00:33:00.170 --> 00:33:03.680
And so in a typical
fire, you've got a bunch

00:33:03.680 --> 00:33:05.040
of fuel coming off of the wood.

00:33:05.040 --> 00:33:08.230
And then it's got to
pull air from the outside

00:33:08.230 --> 00:33:09.784
to react with that.

00:33:09.784 --> 00:33:11.950
But there's too much fuel
in the middle and too much

00:33:11.950 --> 00:33:12.741
air on the outside.

00:33:12.741 --> 00:33:15.180
And somewhere in between
is where the flame happens.

00:33:15.180 --> 00:33:17.220
And where there's too
much fuel, often that

00:33:17.220 --> 00:33:18.760
will cool off and
then be unburned.

00:33:18.760 --> 00:33:21.630
And that's the particulate
smoke, either in droplets

00:33:21.630 --> 00:33:24.420
or solid particles
that get emitted.

00:33:24.420 --> 00:33:27.510
By injecting air
at high velocity,

00:33:27.510 --> 00:33:30.810
we swirl all that stuff together
so that the big chunks of fuel

00:33:30.810 --> 00:33:33.290
and the big pockets of air
get intimate with each other

00:33:33.290 --> 00:33:35.410
and can really mix and
allow that chemistry

00:33:35.410 --> 00:33:37.700
to happen in the environment
where it's nice and hot.

00:33:37.700 --> 00:33:39.580
And you get complete combustion.

00:33:39.580 --> 00:33:42.157
All the fuel gets converted.

00:33:42.157 --> 00:33:42.990
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:33:42.990 --> 00:33:45.270
ETHAN KAY: Thanks.

00:33:45.270 --> 00:33:47.560
AUDIENCE: Hi, thanks for
coming and talking to us.

00:33:47.560 --> 00:33:48.210
Two questions.

00:33:48.210 --> 00:33:50.540
What are the metallic
parts made of,

00:33:50.540 --> 00:33:52.390
like the ones outside
the bigger parts?

00:33:52.390 --> 00:33:54.520
And then how does
the financing usually

00:33:54.520 --> 00:33:57.550
work for people who are
buying these stoves?

00:33:57.550 --> 00:33:59.242
RYAN GIST: Sure.

00:33:59.242 --> 00:34:00.950
There's a combination
of different alloys

00:34:00.950 --> 00:34:03.680
in the stove that are used
in different locations,

00:34:03.680 --> 00:34:06.300
based on the temperature
that they're exposed to,

00:34:06.300 --> 00:34:08.679
based on the
chemistry in the wood,

00:34:08.679 --> 00:34:11.580
whether it be sulphur or
chlorine that may be attacking

00:34:11.580 --> 00:34:13.632
it in a corrosion mechanism.

00:34:13.632 --> 00:34:15.090
You see a lot of
cast iron on here.

00:34:15.090 --> 00:34:18.540
Cast iron is attributed
to durability

00:34:18.540 --> 00:34:19.719
in the markets we operate.

00:34:19.719 --> 00:34:21.719
And people really
trust that material.

00:34:21.719 --> 00:34:24.280
So we always use cast iron
on the top of the stove.

00:34:24.280 --> 00:34:27.239
In this version, there was some
cast iron in the main chamber.

00:34:27.239 --> 00:34:31.710
We've since gone away from
that and gone to an alloy

00:34:31.710 --> 00:34:32.409
that we can use.

00:34:32.409 --> 00:34:35.139
In a thinner wall, we can
reduce weight and cost

00:34:35.139 --> 00:34:37.610
in the stove, which really
improves the last mile

00:34:37.610 --> 00:34:39.636
distribution that Ethan
was talking about.

00:34:39.636 --> 00:34:41.969
When you use you cast iron,
the stove gets pretty heavy.

00:34:41.969 --> 00:34:44.170
And so for someone
on a motorcycle,

00:34:44.170 --> 00:34:46.176
they can only carry one or two.

00:34:46.176 --> 00:34:47.550
The next generation
of this thing

00:34:47.550 --> 00:34:50.440
will be able to carry four,
maybe five, on a motorcycle,

00:34:50.440 --> 00:34:51.960
and get the same
kind of durability

00:34:51.960 --> 00:34:55.040
by using a higher performance
alloy rather than the cast

00:34:55.040 --> 00:34:55.540
iron.

00:34:55.540 --> 00:34:56.710
So it's a whole mix.

00:34:56.710 --> 00:34:59.720
And we work really closely
with Oak Ridge National

00:34:59.720 --> 00:35:03.080
Labs and their combustion
and corrosion lab

00:35:03.080 --> 00:35:06.480
to really find the
optimum materials.

00:35:06.480 --> 00:35:08.760
Typically, really
corrosion resistant,

00:35:08.760 --> 00:35:10.740
heat resistant materials
are very expensive.

00:35:10.740 --> 00:35:12.800
So it's another one of
these balancing acts

00:35:12.800 --> 00:35:15.850
where we have to find the
right trade between cost

00:35:15.850 --> 00:35:17.000
and durability.

00:35:17.000 --> 00:35:19.460
I think we're really close.

00:35:19.460 --> 00:35:21.700
With respect to your
financing question,

00:35:21.700 --> 00:35:25.480
in our first year of operations,
all of our stoves sold

00:35:25.480 --> 00:35:27.710
were with upfront cash.

00:35:27.710 --> 00:35:33.720
So customers would
pay 50-odd dollars

00:35:33.720 --> 00:35:37.820
in cash, which obviously is
a substantial amount of money

00:35:37.820 --> 00:35:39.480
relative to incomes.

00:35:39.480 --> 00:35:42.110
But to our surprise,
we sold stoves

00:35:42.110 --> 00:35:45.980
faster than we had expected
a higher than modeled

00:35:45.980 --> 00:35:47.590
retail price.

00:35:47.590 --> 00:35:49.720
But we realized that
we were probably

00:35:49.720 --> 00:35:55.800
only skimming the more affluent
parts of our target market.

00:35:55.800 --> 00:36:01.050
And so starting in 2015,
we focused exclusively

00:36:01.050 --> 00:36:04.340
on launching what we called
credit-enabled distribution

00:36:04.340 --> 00:36:04.940
channels.

00:36:04.940 --> 00:36:09.790
So these include banks,
microfinance organizations,

00:36:09.790 --> 00:36:13.550
and producer cooperatives
that provide loans to farmers.

00:36:13.550 --> 00:36:18.130
And in those models, the
flavors of financing vary.

00:36:18.130 --> 00:36:24.610
But for instance, in India
our main microfinance partner

00:36:24.610 --> 00:36:29.200
finances the stove for
$2 a month for two years.

00:36:29.200 --> 00:36:31.190
And that obviously
has dramatically

00:36:31.190 --> 00:36:33.450
widened the addressable
market of people that can

00:36:33.450 --> 00:36:34.878
afford to purchase the stove.

