00:38:50.430 --> 00:38:52.671
AUDIENCE: In terms
of size for people--

00:38:52.671 --> 00:38:54.670
I mean, there have been
a number of technologies

00:38:54.670 --> 00:38:57.430
that have been attempted to use
for this, like solar stoves.

00:38:57.430 --> 00:39:02.300
How do you compare, in
terms of size of market

00:39:02.300 --> 00:39:04.124
and in terms of
installed base, compared

00:39:04.124 --> 00:39:05.540
to some of these
other things that

00:39:05.540 --> 00:39:10.228
have been used for the reduction
in pollution and the like?

00:39:12.860 --> 00:39:14.370
ETHAN KAY: Maybe I can start.

00:39:14.370 --> 00:39:15.249
RYAN GIST: Go for it.

00:39:15.249 --> 00:39:17.040
ETHAN KAY: And forgive
a bit of snark here.

00:39:19.840 --> 00:39:24.150
As we were saying in the
talk, that taste of food

00:39:24.150 --> 00:39:26.050
is really culturally specific.

00:39:26.050 --> 00:39:31.650
And from my experience,
and there are exceptions,

00:39:31.650 --> 00:39:34.700
but from my experience,
cooking on a solar stove

00:39:34.700 --> 00:39:37.580
is the equivalent of trying
to microwave a steak.

00:39:37.580 --> 00:39:40.840
And who wants to eat
a microwaved steak?

00:39:40.840 --> 00:39:42.442
There are a few
problems with it.

00:39:42.442 --> 00:39:46.350
One, you need a lot of sunlight.

00:39:46.350 --> 00:39:50.530
And during the monsoon season,
for instance, in India,

00:39:50.530 --> 00:39:54.170
or in the evening, that's
obviously a challenge.

00:39:54.170 --> 00:39:58.130
Secondly, food takes
a really long time

00:39:58.130 --> 00:40:00.040
to prepare on a solar cooker.

00:40:00.040 --> 00:40:03.160
So it's like slow
cooking in the US.

00:40:03.160 --> 00:40:05.860
So you put the food on in
the cooker in the morning.

00:40:05.860 --> 00:40:08.454
You hope it stays sunny all day.

00:40:08.454 --> 00:40:09.870
And in the evening,
you have food.

00:40:09.870 --> 00:40:12.890
But for instance, you
can't make a roti,

00:40:12.890 --> 00:40:15.735
a flat bread on a solar cooker.

00:40:15.735 --> 00:40:17.110
And as I was
joking, you probably

00:40:17.110 --> 00:40:21.069
wouldn't want to grill
your steak on one.

00:40:21.069 --> 00:40:22.610
RYAN GIST: I mean,
you said it great.

00:40:22.610 --> 00:40:25.240
I don't think there's too much
more to add to that, really.

00:40:25.240 --> 00:40:27.920
ETHAN KAY: So yeah, so
solar cookers, I think,

00:40:27.920 --> 00:40:30.100
are appropriate in some
contexts and have gained

00:40:30.100 --> 00:40:31.650
some traction in some contexts.

00:40:31.650 --> 00:40:35.300
But half the planet,
as we were saying,

00:40:35.300 --> 00:40:37.820
cooks with wood, cow
dung, and crop waste.

00:40:37.820 --> 00:40:40.850
And we really feel as a
business that our goal

00:40:40.850 --> 00:40:45.120
is to meet users where they are
in terms of the types of fuels

00:40:45.120 --> 00:40:47.880
that they have available, the
types of dishes that they like

00:40:47.880 --> 00:40:50.060
to cook, and ensuring
that the taste is

00:40:50.060 --> 00:40:52.540
consistent with the meals
that they prepared before

00:40:52.540 --> 00:40:54.810
on an open fire.

00:40:54.810 --> 00:40:56.910
AUDIENCE: So I
just had a question

00:40:56.910 --> 00:41:02.380
about how much of a piece of
wood is, say, incombustible.

00:41:02.380 --> 00:41:03.720
What is perfect?

00:41:03.720 --> 00:41:05.900
And how close are you
to perfect when it

00:41:05.900 --> 00:41:07.360
comes to combusting everything?

00:41:07.360 --> 00:41:08.580
RYAN GIST: Sure.

00:41:08.580 --> 00:41:13.080
I mean, wood is primarily carbon
and hydrogen, mostly carbon.

00:41:13.080 --> 00:41:16.040
When we talk about
burning to completion,

00:41:16.040 --> 00:41:17.610
we can burn all that carbon.

00:41:17.610 --> 00:41:22.030
So there's maybe on an
average piece of wood 3% to 8%

00:41:22.030 --> 00:41:23.240
that's mineral.

00:41:23.240 --> 00:41:25.930
And that's the only part
that's actually not burnable.

00:41:25.930 --> 00:41:29.610
So if you've ever seen the
leftovers after a fire,

00:41:29.610 --> 00:41:31.180
there's a lot of
big black chunks,

00:41:31.180 --> 00:41:33.040
which is the char or carbon.

00:41:33.040 --> 00:41:35.830
And then there's little
bits of white, stringy,

00:41:35.830 --> 00:41:37.040
spider-web-looking material.

00:41:37.040 --> 00:41:39.230
And that white stuff
is mineral ash.

00:41:39.230 --> 00:41:40.740
And that's the only
part of the wood

00:41:40.740 --> 00:41:42.800
that's completely unburnable.

00:41:42.800 --> 00:41:46.610
AUDIENCE: And does the
reduction in total carbon

00:41:46.610 --> 00:41:49.760
ash effect uses that people
have for their stoves?

00:41:49.760 --> 00:41:51.642
Do they have things
to do with the ash?

00:41:51.642 --> 00:41:53.100
RYAN GIST: That's
a great question.

00:41:53.100 --> 00:41:55.820
And we see that a lot,
although what happens

00:41:55.820 --> 00:41:59.810
is in some households, they're
ready to utilize that charcoal.

00:41:59.810 --> 00:42:01.890
And they may have a
specific charcoal stove

00:42:01.890 --> 00:42:02.820
that they might use.

00:42:02.820 --> 00:42:04.660
But in a lot of
homes, it just gets

00:42:04.660 --> 00:42:06.250
disregarded and passed off.

00:42:06.250 --> 00:42:08.104
So we feel like
it's better for us

00:42:08.104 --> 00:42:09.520
to go ahead and
burn that charcoal

00:42:09.520 --> 00:42:12.500
to completion, give them all
that heat energy for cooking.

00:42:12.500 --> 00:42:14.250
If they still need
to purchase or create

00:42:14.250 --> 00:42:16.960
charcoal for a different
cooking task, that's fine.

00:42:16.960 --> 00:42:19.810
But I think we'd rather cover
all those instances where

00:42:19.810 --> 00:42:21.610
people discard the charcoal.

00:42:21.610 --> 00:42:24.410
